          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "1b6b9f97-40eb-4904-be64-6db1703fc6d2",
        "score": 0.595019,
        "text": "The document page is from Section 9: Settlement and Billing of the ERCOT Nodal Protocols, dated February 1, 2025. It lists various sections related to payments and charges within the energy market. These include:\n\n- MRA (Market Resource Adequacy) payments and charges for capital expenditures, deployment events, variable payments, unexcused misconduct, and service charges.\n- Voltage support service payments and charges.\n- Black start services, including hourly standby fee and capacity charges.\n- Payments for emergency operations and real-time revenue neutrality allocation.\n- Emergency response service capacity payments and charges.\n- Firm fuel supply service payments, including hourly standby fee and capacity charges.\n- Real-time settlement for updated day-ahead market ancillary service obligations.\n- Regulation up and down service payments and charges.\n- Responsive reserve payments and charges.\n- Non-spinning reserve service payments and charges.\n- ERCOT contingency reserve service payments and charges.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_9:_Settlement_and_Billing/page_17.jpg",
          "page_num": 17,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 9: Settlement and Billing",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "053fa2ca-d2c1-45b6-81d8-5697777eb760",
        "score": 0.5911423,
        "text": "The document outlines the ERCOT System Administration and User Fees as part of the settlement and billing process.\n\n### ERCOT System Administration Fee\n1. **Authorization and Purpose**: The Public Utility Commission of Texas (PUCT) authorizes ERCOT to charge this fee to fund its budget. The fee is converted into a charge for each Qualified Scheduling Entity (QSE) using a specified formula.\n   \n2. **Posting and Approval**: ERCOT must post the fee on its website. Any changes approved by PUCT must be posted within two business days, including the effective date.\n\n3. **Calculation**: Each QSE pays the fee for every 15-minute Settlement Interval. The formula provided is:\n   \\[\n   \\text{ESACAMT}_q = \\text{LAFF} \\times \\max(0, \\sum \\text{RTAML}_{q,p})\n   \\]\n   - **ESACAMT\\(_q\\)**: The fee for each QSE per interval.\n   - **RTAML\\(_{q,p}\\)**: Real-Time Adjusted Metered Load for each Settlement Point.\n   - **LAFF**: Load Administration Fee Factor.\n   - **q**: A QSE.\n   - **p**: A Settlement Point.\n\n### User Fees\n1. **Approval and Application**: The ERCOT Board approves user fees for services provided to Market Participants or other entities. These fees are set according to Board Policies and Procedures and may include costs for applications, WAN, and interconnection studies.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_9:_Settlement_and_Billing/page_51.jpg",
          "page_num": 51,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 9: Settlement and Billing",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "358386a7-6785-401f-bf79-ddf1ef8de19c",
        "score": 0.58662045,
        "text": "The document outlines procedures related to the Electric Reliability Council of Texas (ERCOT) regarding user fees and transmission billing determinants.\n\n1. **User Fees:**\n   - ERCOT is required to post user fees approved by the ERCOT Board on its website within two business days of any changes.\n   - Market Participants or other entities must pay these approved user fees.\n\n2. **Transmission Billing Determinant Calculation:**\n   - ERCOT provides Market Participants with necessary parameters and formulas to calculate billing charges for using Transmission or Distribution Facilities.\n   - ERCOT is not responsible for billing, collection, or disbursal of payments for transmission access service.\n\n3. **Billing Determinant Data Elements:**\n   - ERCOT calculates and provides data elements annually for Transmission Service Providers (TSPs) and Distribution Service Providers (DSPs) to use as billing determinants.\n   - Data must be provided by December 1 each year and comply with specific regulatory requirements.\n   - Key data elements include:\n     - The 4-Coincident Peak (4-CP) for each DSP and External Load Serving Entity (ELSE).\n     - The ERCOT average 4-CP.\n     - The average 4-CP for each DSP and ELSE coincident to the ERCOT average 4-CP.\n   - The ERCOT average 4-CP is the average of the coincidental MW peaks during June, July, August, and September.\n   - Coincidental MW peak is defined as the highest monthly Settlement Interval 15-minute MW peak for the entire ERCOT Transmission Grid, calculated using a specific formula involving net energy production and transfers.\n\nThe document also references updates to be made in accordance with NPRR995 and NPRR1188.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_9:_Settlement_and_Billing/page_52.jpg",
          "page_num": 52,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 9: Settlement and Billing",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "7b1f85fa-04ed-4a54-919d-20d6f3cee8d6",
        "score": 0.5858159,
        "text": "The document page is from the ERCOT Nodal Protocols, specifically Section 7 on Congestion Revenue Rights. It details the calculations and definitions related to the payment and charge of Point-to-Point (PTP) Obligation and Option bids in Congestion Revenue Rights (CRR) Auctions.\n\n1. **Definitions and Variables:**\n   - **OBLSAMT**: The PTP Obligation Sale Amount for a CRR Account Holder per source and sink pair in a CRR Auction, calculated based on the MW quantity of PTP Obligation offers.\n   - **OBLPR**: The PTP Obligation Price per source and sink pair, representing the clearing price of a PTP Obligation in a CRR Auction.\n   - **OBLS**: The PTP Obligation Sale per CRR Account Holder, indicating the MW quantity of PTP Obligation offers.\n   - **Variables**: \n     - **crrh**: A CRR Account Holder.\n     - **j**: A source Settlement Point.\n     - **k**: A sink Settlement Point.\n     - **a**: A CRR Auction.\n\n2. **Payment Calculation:**\n   - ERCOT pays each CRR Account Holder for PTP Option offers awarded in a CRR Auction. The payment for each source and sink pair for a given Time of Use (TOU) period is calculated using the formula:\n     \\[\n     OPTSAMT_{crrh, (j, k), a} = (-1) \\times OPTPR_{(j, k), a} \\times OPTS_{crrh, (j, k), a}\n     \\]\n   - **OPTSAMT**: PTP Option Sale Amount.\n   - **OPTPR**: PTP Option Price.\n   - **OPTS**: PTP Option Sale.\n\n3. **Charge Calculation:**\n   - ERCOT charges each CRR Account Holder for PTP Obligation bids awarded in a CRR Auction. The charge for each source and sink pair for a given Operating Hour is calculated using the formula:\n     \\[\n     OBLPAMT_{crrh, (j, k), a} = OBLPR_{(j, k), a} \\times OBLP_{crrh, (j, k), a}\n     \\]\n\nThis section provides a structured approach to determining financial transactions related to CRR Auctions, ensuring clarity in the calculation of payments and charges for market participants.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_7_-_Congestion_Revenue_Rights/page_34.jpg",
          "page_num": 34,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 7 - Congestion Revenue Rights",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  "error": null,
  "metadata": {}
}

steps.content:
{
  "success": true,
  "data": {
    "query": "\"Resource Interconnection Handbook\" ERCOT interconnection study process",
    "num_results": 10,
    "filters_applied": {
      "market": null,
      "data_type": null,
