    },
    "documents": [
      {
        "id": "3f904d22-d2ca-4207-86e8-b77cfe7c073e",
        "score": 0.6719438,
        "text": "The document outlines procedures related to the ERCOT system, focusing on the construction and management of interconnections. Key points include:\n\n1. **Coordination and Consistency**: ERCOT, TSPs, DCTOs, and Resource Entities must coordinate to ensure that Transmission Elements are consistently defined across operational models.\n\n2. **Unique Identifiers**: Each Transmission Element must have a unique identifier, following a naming convention developed with input from TSPs and approved by the Technical Advisory Committee (TAC). ERCOT will provide details of all Transmission Elements to Market Participants daily.\n\n3. **Southern Cross Requirements**: Southern Cross must provide ERCOT with notice and financial security to proceed with interconnection construction. They must also cover the entire project cost and have an agreement with a TSP.\n\n4. **Non-Operational Changes**: If a TSP submits a NOMCR for non-operational changes, ERCOT will implement the request.\n\nThe document includes specific amendments (NPRR857) to ensure Southern Cross meets financial and procedural conditions for interconnection projects.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_3:_Management_Activities_for_the_ERCOT_System/page_173.jpg",
          "page_num": 173,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 3: Management Activities for the ERCOT System",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "afea3525-90ac-4b00-8ecb-e71fcce1e379",
        "score": 0.65706444,
        "text": "The document outlines procedures for analyzing resource adequacy within the ERCOT system, specifically focusing on the calculation of aggregate resource capacity. Key points include:\n\n1. **Outage Scheduler and COP**: ERCOT uses the Outage Scheduler and the Current Operating Plan (COP) to calculate aggregate capacity from Generation Resources and Load Resources. These are projected to be available in the ERCOT Region and Forecast Zones, which align with the 2003 ERCOT Congestion Management Zones (CMZs).\n\n2. **Resource Mapping**: Each resource is mapped to a Forecast Zone during registration.\n\n3. **Hourly Calculations**: ERCOT calculates aggregate hourly capacities for Generation Resources and Load Resources on a rolling basis for the next seven days.\n\n4. **Inclusion of ESRs**: Upon system implementation, Energy Storage Resources (ESRs) will also be included in these calculations.\n\n5. **Renewable Resources**: Projections for Intermittent Renewable Resources (IRRs) must align with capacity availability estimates and wind profiles, developed in collaboration with ERCOT's Technical Advisory Committee and approved by the ERCOT Board.\n\nThe document also notes updates to be made upon system implementation, as indicated by NPRR1014 and NPRR1029.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_3:_Management_Activities_for_the_ERCOT_System/page_49.jpg",
          "page_num": 49,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 3: Management Activities for the ERCOT System",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "8ae5b384-e7b7-4cc8-b014-f50818819ec3",
        "score": 0.655862,
        "text": "The document outlines procedures related to the ERCOT (Electric Reliability Council of Texas) system management, specifically focusing on the interconnection and transmission elements:\n\n1. **Interconnection Requirements**: Southern Cross must provide ERCOT with a notice to proceed with construction and financial security for funding the interconnection facilities. ERCOT will use the physical characteristics, ratings, and operational limits of all transmission elements to define network models for market participants. If a Private Use Network is not registered, equivalent model data from TSPs will be used.\n\n2. **Network Operations Model**: Accurate modeling of transmission elements is crucial for the ERCOT market. ERCOT manages this by sending Base Points and pricing signals to market participants, which affects power flows and ensures reliability. This involves managing within ratings provided by TSPs and Resource Entities, using Generic Transmission Constraints and Limits.\n\n3. **Amendment Conditions**: An amendment (NPRR857) specifies conditions under which Southern Cross must provide funds to cover project costs and sign an interconnection agreement with a TSP. This includes providing notice to proceed with construction and financial security.\n\n4. **Equipment Ratings**: TSPs and Resource Entities must provide ERCOT with equipment ratings and updates as required. ERCOT may request these entities to supply necessary information for maintaining system reliability.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_3:_Management_Activities_for_the_ERCOT_System/page_154.jpg",
          "page_num": 154,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 3: Management Activities for the ERCOT System",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "576499b1-2021-46ed-b01e-3f4ff68f3ea8",
        "score": 0.65441823,
        "text": "The document page is from Section 11 of the ERCOT Nodal Protocols, focusing on data acquisition and aggregation. It outlines procedures for handling different types of data:\n\n1. **ERCOT Read ESI ID Data Extract**:\n   - Selects all ERCOT read ESI IDs for market participants.\n   - Provides interval data for each channel associated with an ESI ID.\n\n2. **Treatment of ERCOT Polled Settlement Resource ID Data**:\n   - ERCOT is identified as the MRE (Meter Reading Entity).\n   - Models and populates data to ensure netting and aggregation conform to ERCOT Protocols.\n   - Makes RID interval and SCADA data available to relevant entities.\n   - The data extract selects all ERCOT read RIDs for market participants and provides interval data for each channel.\n   - Provides interval data to TSPs/DSPs by noon on the tenth business day after reading the EPS meter.\n   - Updates revised data to TSP/DSP by noon of the tenth business day after any edits.\n\n3. **Treatment of ERCOT-Polled Settlement Energy Storage Resource Load Data**:\n   - For WSL and Non-WSL ESR Charging Load, ERCOT is identified as the MRE.\n   - Models and populates data to ensure netting and aggregation conform to ERCOT Protocols.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_11:_Data_Acquisition_and_Aggregation/page_12.jpg",
          "page_num": 12,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 11: Data Acquisition and Aggregation",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "0bbb0651-19f5-4690-9cb2-ce4e1530f83f",
        "score": 0.6424182,
        "text": "The document outlines procedures for the Electric Reliability Council of Texas (ERCOT) regarding topology and model verification, and the submission of declarations for natural gas pipeline coordination.\n\n### Topology and Model Verification\n1. **Notification and Verification**: ERCOT must notify the appropriate Transmission Service Provider (TSP) or Resource Entity about constraints identified in the evaluation of chronic congestion. The TSP or Resource Entity must verify the accuracy of data in the Network Operations Model and Updated Network Model, including transmission facility ratings.\n\n2. **System Implementation Conditions**: A note specifies conditions under which Southern Cross must provide funds and sign an interconnection agreement with a TSP. The TSP must then notify ERCOT about the construction and financial security for the interconnection.\n\n3. **Inaccuracies and Coordination**: If inaccuracies are found in the models or facility configuration, ERCOT must coordinate with the facility owner to update the ratings as needed.\n\n### Submission of Declarations of Natural Gas Pipeline Coordination\n1. **Declaration Requirement**: Resource Entities using natural gas must submit a declaration to ERCOT, confirming communication with pipeline operators to assess impacts on resource availability during peak load seasons.\n\n2. **Outage Reporting**: If a Resource Entity or its Qualified Scheduling Entity (QSE) knows of any pipeline-related issues affecting resource availability, they must report the outage or derate in the ERCOT Outage Scheduler promptly.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_3:_Management_Activities_for_the_ERCOT_System/page_323.jpg",
          "page_num": 323,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 3: Management Activities for the ERCOT System",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "da9829f9-5976-4bd5-ad2b-306b9dcb56ce",
        "score": 0.6392103,
        "text": "The document outlines management activities for the ERCOT system, focusing on the coordination and registration of various resource entities. Key points include:\n\n1. **Resource Coordination**: ERCOT coordinates with Resource Entities to model and map Load Resources to appropriate loads in the Network Operations Model.\n\n2. **Distribution Generation Resources (DGR) and Energy Storage**: Resource Entities representing DGR or Distribution Energy Storage Resources (DESR) must provide ERCOT and related parties with detailed information and telemetry for registration and mapping in the Network Operations Model.\n\n3. **Settlement Only Distribution Generators (SODG/SODESS)**: These entities must register with ERCOT and provide necessary information for mapping in the Network Operations Model. A note indicates a future replacement of paragraph (4) with updated requirements upon system implementation.\n\n4. **Split Generation Resources**: These resources must provide information for their share of generation to be represented in the Network Operations Model, ensuring connection to the ERCOT Transmission Grid.\n\n5. **DC Tie Resources**: ERCOT will create a DC Tie Resource to represent generation injection into the ERCOT Transmission Grid from DC Ties. \n\nOverall, the document emphasizes the importance of detailed information sharing and coordination for effective resource management within the ERCOT system.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_3:_Management_Activities_for_the_ERCOT_System/page_183.jpg",
          "page_num": 183,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 3: Management Activities for the ERCOT System",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "6b9d65a7-611b-419e-8ead-078b588fb88c",
        "score": 0.63677096,
        "text": "The document outlines management activities for the ERCOT system, focusing on the responsibilities of Resource Entities for Intermittent Renewable Resources (IRR) synchronized to the ERCOT system. Key points include:\n\n1. **Reactive Capability Curve Requirements**:\n   - Ensure the lowest MW point reflects 0 MVAr leading and lagging reactive capability.\n   - Ensure the second-lowest MW point accurately reflects the IRR's leading and lagging reactive capability at its Low Sustainable Limit (LSL).\n\n2. **Telemetry and AVR Status**:\n   - Send an \"Off\" status to ERCOT when the IRR is synchronized but not producing reactive power.\n\n3. **Stable Reactive Power Output**:\n   - Provide stable reactive power at all MW levels within the IRR's capability.\n   - Set the IRR LSL to 0 MW or the lowest MW level (not exceeding 1 MW) for stable reactive power provision.\n\n4. **Synchronization and Desynchronization**:\n   - Send an \"On\" status when synchronized and not producing real power, ensuring reactive control is working.\n   - Physically desynchronize inverters when not producing real power to avoid providing reactive power.\n\n5. **Implementation Conditions for Southern Cross Transmission LLC**:\n   - Southern Cross must provide ERCOT with funds for the project's estimated cost and sign an interconnection agreement with a Transmission Service Provider (TSP).\n   - ERCOT must receive notice of the interconnection's construction and financial security for funding the facilities.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_3:_Management_Activities_for_the_ERCOT_System/page_303.jpg",
          "page_num": 303,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 3: Management Activities for the ERCOT System",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "010d6687-a15a-490b-a3b0-6c77d217464e",
        "score": 0.63607347,
        "text": "The document is a section from the ERCOT Nodal Protocols, specifically focusing on management activities for the ERCOT system. It outlines requirements for modeling transmission elements and resources.\n\n1. **Transmission Elements**: \n   - Lists parameters needed for modeling, such as voltage, switching device names, connectivity, nominal voltage, and other necessary data.\n   - ERCOT Operating Guides must include parameters for standard reactor and capacitor switching plans for the Network Operations Model.\n   - ERCOT is responsible for modeling devices and providing copies of switching plans to market participants. Changes in guidelines or plans must be communicated to ERCOT before implementation, except in emergencies.\n\n2. **Modeling of Resources and Transmission Loads**:\n   - Each Resource Entity must provide ERCOT and its interconnecting Transmission Service Provider (TSP) with information about its Generation Resources, SOGs, and Load Resources.\n   - All types of Transmission Generation Resources and other specified generators must be modeled to provide equivalent generation injections to the ERCOT Transmission Grid.\n   - ERCOT coordinates the modeling of resources to ensure consistency between TSP models and ERCOT models.\n\n3. **Implementation Note**:\n   - A note indicates a replacement paragraph for future implementation, detailing similar requirements with slight modifications, including the addition of Settlement Only Transmission Energy Storage Systems (SOTESSs).\n\n4. **Load Resources**:\n   - Resource Entities representing Load Resources or Aggregate Load Resources must provide relevant information to ERCOT and interconnecting Distribution Service Providers (DSPs).",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_3:_Management_Activities_for_the_ERCOT_System/page_182.jpg",
          "page_num": 182,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 3: Management Activities for the ERCOT System",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "9f77b943-1023-4b0f-9ce3-1da76701cfa1",
        "score": 0.63570607,
        "text": "The document outlines protocols for managing communications regarding resource and transmission facilities outages within the ERCOT system. It specifies that ERCOT must report monthly statistics on how planned resource outages compare with actual outages and post these on their website.\n\nKey points include:\n\n1. **Single Point of Contact**: \n   - All communications about planned, maintenance, or rescheduled outages must be between ERCOT and a designated \"Single Point of Contact\" for each Transmission Service Provider (TSP) or Resource Entity.\n   - Communications must be electronic, and the TSP or Resource Entity must identify a primary and alternate contact method.\n   - A Notice of Change of Information (NCI) form must be submitted when changes occur to the Single Point of Contact.\n\n2. **Special Conditions for Southern Cross**:\n   - Upon meeting certain conditions, Southern Cross must provide funds to ERCOT and sign an interconnection agreement with a TSP.\n   - Southern Cross must notify ERCOT to proceed with construction and provide financial security for the interconnection facilities.\n\n3. **Availability**:\n   - The Single Point of Contact must be available 24/7 for each Resource Entity and TSP.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_3:_Management_Activities_for_the_ERCOT_System/page_12.jpg",
          "page_num": 12,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 3: Management Activities for the ERCOT System",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "edc57599-8869-4fe6-a402-213bcaa63557",
        "score": 0.6324551,
        "text": "The document outlines management activities for the ERCOT system, focusing on system implementation and interconnection agreements. Key points include:\n\n1. **Interconnection Conditions**: Southern Cross must provide ERCOT with funds to cover project costs and sign an interconnection agreement with a Transmission Service Provider (TSP). ERCOT requires notice and financial security from Southern Cross to proceed with construction.\n\n2. **Protective Measures**: TSPs, DCTOs, and Resource Entities can implement protective relay and control systems to de-energize faulty equipment, ensuring safety and preventing equipment failure. They must adhere to industry standards and provide ERCOT with Relay Loadability Ratings.\n\n3. **Network Operations Model**: Must use rating categories for Transmission Elements as defined in ERCOT Operating Guides.\n\n4. **Transmission Buses**: ERCOT will model each Electrical Bus over 60 kV for switching stations or transmission loads. TSPs and Resource Entities must provide ERCOT with information on Transmission Elements and Parameters, including equipment owners and operators, following specific naming conventions.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_3:_Management_Activities_for_the_ERCOT_System/page_176.jpg",
          "page_num": 176,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 3: Management Activities for the ERCOT System",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
