        "score": 0.63677096,
        "text": "The document outlines management activities for the ERCOT system, focusing on the responsibilities of Resource Entities for Intermittent Renewable Resources (IRR) synchronized to the ERCOT system. Key points include:\n\n1. **Reactive Capability Curve Requirements**:\n   - Ensure the lowest MW point reflects 0 MVAr leading and lagging reactive capability.\n   - Ensure the second-lowest MW point accurately reflects the IRR's leading and lagging reactive capability at its Low Sustainable Limit (LSL).\n\n2. **Telemetry and AVR Status**:\n   - Send an \"Off\" status to ERCOT when the IRR is synchronized but not producing reactive power.\n\n3. **Stable Reactive Power Output**:\n   - Provide stable reactive power at all MW levels within the IRR's capability.\n   - Set the IRR LSL to 0 MW or the lowest MW level (not exceeding 1 MW) for stable reactive power provision.\n\n4. **Synchronization and Desynchronization**:\n   - Send an \"On\" status when synchronized and not producing real power, ensuring reactive control is working.\n   - Physically desynchronize inverters when not producing real power to avoid providing reactive power.\n\n5. **Implementation Conditions for Southern Cross Transmission LLC**:\n   - Southern Cross must provide ERCOT with funds for the project's estimated cost and sign an interconnection agreement with a Transmission Service Provider (TSP).\n   - ERCOT must receive notice of the interconnection's construction and financial security for funding the facilities.",
